        <id>986</id>
        <aid>986</aid>
        <answer>Not applicable / Unsafe to answer.</answer>
        <language>en</language>
      </row>
      <row>
        <id>987</id>
        <aid>987</aid>
        <answer>Large spending can be approved without a clear authority, threshold or second check.</answer>
        <language>en</language>
      </row>
      <row>
        <id>988</id>
        <aid>988</aid>
        <answer>Spending approval rules exist informally, but they are not consistently recorded.</answer>
        <language>en</language>
      </row>
      <row>
        <id>989</id>
        <aid>989</aid>
        <answer>Some spending thresholds and approval rules exist, but funder-facing evidence is incomplete.</answer>
        <language>en</language>
      </row>
      <row>
        <id>990</id>
        <aid>990</aid>
        <answer>Large spending approval is mostly clear, with minor documentation gaps.</answer>
        <language>en</language>
      </row>
      <row>
        <id>991</id>
        <aid>991</aid>
        <answer>Spending authority, thresholds and approval records are clear, current and used in practice.</answer>
        <language>en</language>
      </row>
      <row>
        <id>992</id>
        <aid>992</aid>
        <answer>Not applicable / Unsafe to answer.</answer>
        <language>en</language>
      </row>
      <row>
        <id>993</id>
        <aid>993</aid>
        <answer>We are not yet using this asset in funding conversations or proposals.</answer>
        <language>en</language>
      </row>
      <row>
        <id>994</id>
        <aid>994</aid>
        <answer>This asset exists in fragments, memories or informal records, but it is not organised for funders.</answer>
        <language>en</language>
      </row>
      <row>
        <id>995</id>
        <aid>995</aid>
        <answer>We use this asset sometimes, but not consistently or strongly enough to improve funder confidence.</answer>
        <language>en</language>
      </row>
      <row>
        <id>996</id>
        <aid>996</aid>
        <answer>We usually use this asset well, with minor packaging or verification gaps.</answer>
        <language>en</language>
      </row>
      <row>
        <id>997</id>
        <aid>997</aid>
        <answer>This asset is clearly packaged, credible, safe to use, and actively improves funding opportunity or bargaining power.</answer>
        <language>en</language>
      </row>
      <row>
        <id>998</id>
        <aid>998</aid>
        <answer>Not applicable / Unsafe to answer.</answer>
        <language>en</language>
      </row>
      <row>
        <id>1053</id>
        <aid>1053</aid>
        <answer>Opportunity found — we hear about funding opportunities late, by chance, or through cold public calls.</answer>
        <language>en</language>
      </row>
      <row>
        <id>1054</id>
        <aid>1054</aid>
        <answer>Eligibility checked — we often discover too late that the funder, geography, status, grant size, or route does not fit.</answer>
        <language>en</language>
      </row>
      <row>
        <id>1055</id>
        <aid>1055</aid>
        <answer>Application submitted — we submit, but the application may be rushed, generic, incomplete, or not strategically chosen.</answer>
        <language>en</language>
      </row>
      <row>
        <id>1056</id>
        <aid>1056</aid>
        <answer>Proposal review — applications are received but do not move into conversation, shortlist, clarification, or due diligence.</answer>
        <language>en</language>
      </row>
      <row>
        <id>1057</id>
        <aid>1057</aid>
        <answer>Conversation / clarification — we reach some interest, but do not convert it into a strong next step.</answer>
        <language>en</language>
      </row>
      <row>
        <id>1058</id>
        <aid>1058</aid>
        <answer>Due diligence — documents, controls, proof, policies, risk or verification slow down or block progress.</answer>
        <language>en</language>
      </row>
      <row>
        <id>1059</id>
        <aid>1059</aid>
        <answer>Budget / contract — the money, terms, grant size, receiving route, or compliance burden becomes difficult.</answer>
        <language>en</language>
      </row>
      <row>
        <id>1060</id>
        <aid>1060</aid>
        <answer>Award / renewal — we win or nearly win, but do not convert into renewal, bridge funding, referral, or repeat support.</answer>
        <language>en</language>
      </row>
      <row>
        <id>1061</id>
        <aid>1061</aid>
        <answer>Not sure yet — the pattern is not clear.</answer>
        <language>en</language>
      </row>
      <row>
        <id>1062</id>
        <aid>1062</aid>
        <answer>Not applicable / Unsafe to answer.</answer>
        <language>en</language>
      </row>
      <row>
        <id>1076</id>
        <aid>1076</aid>
        <answer>Awarded or renewed, but not often enough to meet the need</answer>
        <language>en</language>
      </row>
      <row>
        <id>1077</id>
        <aid>1077</aid>
        <answer>Partial funding or smaller-than-needed support</answer>
        <language>en</language>
      </row>
      <row>
        <id>1078</id>
        <aid>1078</aid>
        <answer>Pending or awaiting response for a long time</answer>
        <language>en</language>
      </row>
      <row>
        <id>1079</id>
        <aid>1079</aid>
        <answer>No response / silence</answer>
        <language>en</language>
      </row>
      <row>
        <id>1080</id>
        <aid>1080</aid>
        <answer>Rejected / declined</answer>
        <language>en</language>
      </row>
      <row>
        <id>1081</id>
        <aid>1081</aid>
        <answer>Asked to reapply later</answer>
        <language>en</language>
      </row>
      <row>
        <id>1082</id>
        <aid>1082</aid>
        <answer>Withdrawn because fit, safety, timing, or requirements became difficult</answer>
        <language>en</language>
      </row>
      <row>
        <id>1083</id>
        <aid>1083</aid>
        <answer>Other pattern</answer>
        <language>en</language>
      </row>
      <row>
        <id>1084</id>
        <aid>1084</aid>
        <answer>Not sure</answer>
        <language>en</language>
      </row>
      <row>
        <id>1085</id>
        <aid>1085</aid>
        <answer>Not applicable / Unsafe to answer</answer>
        <language>en</language>
      </row>
      <row>
        <id>1086</id>
        <aid>1086</aid>
        <answer>We usually do not follow up after rejection, silence, or delay.</answer>
        <language>en</language>
      </row>
      <row>
        <id>1087</id>
        <aid>1087</aid>
        <answer>We sometimes send thanks or a short response, but do not usually ask for feedback or next steps.</answer>
        <language>en</language>
      </row>
      <row>
        <id>1088</id>
        <aid>1088</aid>
        <answer>We sometimes ask for feedback, but learning is not consistently documented or used.</answer>
        <language>en</language>
      </row>
      <row>
        <id>1089</id>
        <aid>1089</aid>
        <answer>We usually follow up, capture feedback, and keep the relationship warm where appropriate.</answer>
        <language>en</language>
      </row>
      <row>
        <id>1090</id>
        <aid>1090</aid>
        <answer>We consistently follow up, document lessons, repair materials, and agree a next route or timing where possible.</answer>
        <language>en</language>
      </row>
      <row>
        <id>1091</id>
        <aid>1091</aid>
        <answer>Not applicable / Unsafe to answer.</answer>
        <language>en</language>
      </row>
      <row>
        <id>1092</id>
        <aid>1092</aid>
        <answer>A funder would currently struggle to verify our work through public sources.</answer>
        <language>en</language>
      </row>
      <row>
        <id>1093</id>
        <aid>1093</aid>
        <answer>Public signals exist but are outdated, thin, or inconsistent.</answer>
        <language>en</language>
      </row>
      <row>
        <id>1094</id>
        <aid>1094</aid>
        <answer>Verification is possible, but we could provide stronger public signals.</answer>
        <language>en</language>
      </row>
      <row>
        <id>1095</id>
        <aid>1095</aid>
        <answer>Our public presence mostly confirms our legitimacy and activity.</answer>
        <language>en</language>
      </row>
      <row>
        <id>1096</id>
        <aid>1096</aid>
        <answer>Our public presence is current, safe, credible, and easy for funders to verify.</answer>
        <language>en</language>
      </row>
      <row>
        <id>1097</id>
        <aid>1097</aid>
        <answer>Not applicable / Unsafe to answer.</answer>
        <language>en</language>
      </row>
      <row>
        <id>1098</id>
        <aid>1098</aid>
        <answer>We do not yet have previous grants or funded partnerships that can support our reputation.</answer>
        <language>en</language>
      </row>
      <row>
        <id>1099</id>
        <aid>1099</aid>
        <answer>Previous grant relationships exist, but reporting, close-out, communication or trust signals are unclear.</answer>
        <language>en</language>
      </row>
      <row>
        <id>1100</id>
        <aid>1100</aid>
        <answer>Some previous grants or partnerships support our reputation, but the evidence is mixed or incomplete.</answer>
        <language>en</language>
      </row>
      <row>
        <id>1101</id>
        <aid>1101</aid>
        <answer>Most previous grant behaviour shows reliability, with minor gaps to explain or document.</answer>
        <language>en</language>
      </row>
      <row>
        <id>1102</id>
        <aid>1102</aid>
        <answer>Previous grants or funded partnerships strongly show reliable delivery, reporting, communication and close-out.</answer>
        <language>en</language>
      </row>
      <row>
        <id>1103</id>
        <aid>1103</aid>
        <answer>Not applicable / Unsafe to answer.</answer>
        <language>en</language>
      </row>
      <row>
        <id>1104</id>
        <aid>1104</aid>
        <answer>Previous relationships are not currently usable for renewal, bridge funding, referral, or warm introductions.</answer>
        <language>en</language>
      </row>
      <row>
        <id>1105</id>
        <aid>1105</aid>
        <answer>Some past relationships exist, but they are cold, unclear, or not maintained.</answer>
        <language>en</language>
      </row>
      <row>
        <id>1106</id>
        <aid>1106</aid>
        <answer>A few renewal, bridge-funding, or referral routes may exist but need active repair.</answer>
        <language>en</language>
      </row>
      <row>
        <id>1107</id>
        <aid>1107</aid>
        <answer>Several previous relationships could support renewal, bridge funding, or referrals with minor preparation.</answer>
        <language>en</language>
      </row>
      <row>
        <id>1108</id>
        <aid>1108</aid>
        <answer>Previous funders or partners are actively maintained and usable for renewal, bridge funding, or referral routes.</answer>
        <language>en</language>
      </row>
      <row>
        <id>1109</id>
        <aid>1109</aid>
        <answer>Not applicable / Unsafe to answer.</answer>
        <language>en</language>
      </row>
      <row>
        <id>1110</id>
        <aid>1110</aid>
        <answer>There is no shared fundraising or resourcing strategy guiding what to pursue and what to decline.</answer>
        <language>en</language>
      </row>
      <row>
        <id>1111</id>
        <aid>1111</aid>
        <answer>Ideas exist, but they live in conversations or one person’s head rather than a usable plan.</answer>
        <language>en</language>
      </row>
      <row>
        <id>1112</id>
        <aid>1112</aid>
        <answer>A plan exists, but it is not consistently used to choose funders, timing, owners, or next actions.</answer>
        <language>en</language>
      </row>
      <row>
        <id>1113</id>
        <aid>1113</aid>
        <answer>The strategy mostly guides priorities, owners and review rhythm, with minor gaps.</answer>
        <language>en</language>
      </row>
      <row>
        <id>1114</id>
        <aid>1114</aid>
        <answer>The strategy is current, owned, reviewed, and actively used to make funding decisions.</answer>
        <language>en</language>
      </row>
      <row>
        <id>1115</id>
        <aid>1115</aid>
        <answer>Not applicable / Unsafe to answer.</answer>
        <language>en</language>
      </row>
      <row>
        <id>1116</id>
        <aid>1116</aid>
        <answer>There is no live funder pipeline or tracker that the team uses.</answer>
        <language>en</language>
      </row>
      <row>
        <id>1117</id>
        <aid>1117</aid>
        <answer>A funder list or spreadsheet exists, but it does not consistently show owner, next step, deadline, route, fit, or outcome.</answer>
        <language>en</language>
      </row>
      <row>
        <id>1118</id>
        <aid>1118</aid>
        <answer>A tracker exists, but some prospects, deadlines, routes or next actions are missing or outdated.</answer>
        <language>en</language>
      </row>
      <row>
        <id>1119</id>
        <aid>1119</aid>
        <answer>The pipeline is mostly current and shows prospects, routes, deadlines, contacts, owners and next steps.</answer>
        <language>en</language>
      </row>
      <row>
        <id>1120</id>
        <aid>1120</aid>
        <answer>The pipeline or CRM is live, owned, updated, and used to decide where effort should go next.</answer>
        <language>en</language>
      </row>
      <row>
        <id>1121</id>
        <aid>1121</aid>
        <answer>Not applicable / Unsafe to answer.</answer>
        <language>en</language>
      </row>
      <row>
        <id>1122</id>
        <aid>1122</aid>
        <answer>Reports are often late, missing, or not strong enough to reuse as proof.</answer>
        <language>en</language>
      </row>
      <row>
        <id>1123</id>
        <aid>1123</aid>
        <answer>Some reports are produced, but they are inconsistent, hard to find, or weak on results and learning.</answer>
        <language>en</language>
      </row>
      <row>
        <id>1124</id>
        <aid>1124</aid>
        <answer>Reports are usually produced, but timing, quality, or evidence strength varies.</answer>
        <language>en</language>
      </row>
      <row>
        <id>1125</id>
        <aid>1125</aid>
        <answer>Most reports are timely and useful, with minor gaps in evidence, finance, or learning.</answer>
        <language>en</language>
      </row>
      <row>
        <id>1126</id>
        <aid>1126</aid>
        <answer>Reports are timely, clear, evidence-backed, financially consistent, and usable as proof for future funders.</answer>
        <language>en</language>
      </row>
      <row>
        <id>1127</id>
        <aid>1127</aid>
        <answer>Not applicable / Unsafe to answer.</answer>
        <language>en</language>
      </row>
      <row>
        <id>1128</id>
        <aid>1128</aid>
        <answer>Missing: we do not yet have this document or evidence item.</answer>
        <language>en</language>
      </row>
      <row>
        <id>1129</id>
        <aid>1129</aid>
        <answer>Exists but not ready: it is draft, outdated, scattered, or incomplete.</answer>
        <language>en</language>
      </row>
      <row>
        <id>1130</id>
        <aid>1130</aid>
        <answer>Usable internally: it exists, but needs review before sharing with a funder.</answer>
        <language>en</language>
      </row>
      <row>
        <id>1131</id>
        <aid>1131</aid>
        <answer>Shareable with care: it is current, but may need minor updates, approval, or redaction.</answer>
        <language>en</language>
      </row>
      <row>
        <id>1132</id>
        <aid>1132</aid>
        <answer>Funder-ready: it is current, approved or verified, easy to find, and safe to share through the right route.</answer>
        <language>en</language>
      </row>
      <row>
        <id>1133</id>
        <aid>1133</aid>
        <answer>Protected evidence: it exists, but should be anonymised, redacted, or verified privately.</answer>
        <language>en</language>
      </row>
      <row>
        <id>1134</id>
        <aid>1134</aid>
        <answer>Not required for our structure, route, or funder type.</answer>
        <language>en</language>
      </row>
      <row>
        <id>1135</id>
        <aid>1135</aid>
        <answer>Low confidence: we cannot safely or clearly verify this yet.</answer>
        <language>en</language>
      </row>
      <row>
        <id>1136</id>
        <aid>1136</aid>
        <answer>Some confidence: evidence is mostly informal, incomplete, or held by one person.</answer>
        <language>en</language>
      </row>
      <row>
        <id>1137</id>
        <aid>1137</aid>
        <answer>Moderate confidence: internal records exist but need checking, updating, or approval.</answer>
        <language>en</language>
      </row>
      <row>
        <id>1138</id>
        <aid>1138</aid>
        <answer>High confidence: records are current, consistent, and can support due diligence.</answer>
        <language>en</language>
      </row>
      <row>
        <id>1139</id>
        <aid>1139</aid>
        <answer>Protected confidence: evidence is strong but must be anonymised, redacted, or privately verified.</answer>
        <language>en</language>
      </row>
      <row>
        <id>1140</id>
        <aid>1140</aid>
        <answer>Not required / not applicable for our route.</answer>
        <language>en</language>
      </row>
    </rows>
