        <language>en</language>
      </row>
      <row>
        <id>110</id>
        <qid>5090</qid>
        <question>Unsafe to answer</question>
        <help />
        <script />
        <language>en</language>
      </row>
      <row>
        <id>111</id>
        <qid>244</qid>
        <question>What was the approximate annual operating budget in the last completed financial year?</question>
        <help>&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Help:&lt;/strong&gt; Budget size helps test grant-size fit and due-diligence expectations. Use local currency or prefer not to say if exact USD bands are not useful or safe.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Example:&lt;/strong&gt; Use the safest accurate answer. If exact details create risk, use an approximate answer or choose Not applicable / Unsafe to answer.&lt;/p&gt;</help>
        <script />
        <language>en</language>
      </row>
      <row>
        <id>113</id>
        <qid>246</qid>
        <question>How much funding is currently being sought?</question>
        <help>&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Help:&lt;/strong&gt; The amount sought affects funder fit, due diligence intensity, budget review, and whether the ask matches current systems.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Example:&lt;/strong&gt; Use the safest accurate answer. If exact details create risk, use an approximate answer or choose Not applicable / Unsafe to answer.&lt;/p&gt;</help>
        <script />
        <language>en</language>
      </row>
      <row>
        <id>114</id>
        <qid>247</qid>
        <question>What is the primary purpose of the funding sought? Select all that apply.</question>
        <help>&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Help:&lt;/strong&gt; This helps funders and the report understand what the money is really for, including costs that are often hidden or underfunded.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Example:&lt;/strong&gt; Select all major uses of the funding request, including infrastructure, equipment, team costs, core costs and safeguarding where relevant.&lt;/p&gt;</help>
        <script />
        <language>en</language>
      </row>
      <row>
        <id>129</id>
        <qid>248</qid>
        <question>How urgent is the funding need?</question>
        <help>&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Help:&lt;/strong&gt; Timing affects whether the best next move is apply, repair, build a relationship, use a rapid-response route, or prepare for the next cycle.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Example:&lt;/strong&gt; Use the safest accurate answer. If exact details create risk, use an approximate answer or choose Not applicable / Unsafe to answer.&lt;/p&gt;</help>
        <script />
        <language>en</language>
      </row>
      <row>
        <id>130</id>
        <qid>249</qid>
        <question>Which current or past funders, partners, fiscal hosts, or major supporters matter for this assessment? Select all that apply.</question>
        <help>&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Help:&lt;/strong&gt; Past and current support can shape trust, renewal routes, references, risk perception and funder fit.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Example:&lt;/strong&gt; Select supporter types that can affect how funders read your credibility, track record, receiving route or future opportunity.&lt;/p&gt;</help>
        <script />
        <language>en</language>
      </row>
      <row>
        <id>131</id>
        <qid>250</qid>
        <question>How many funding applications or funding asks were submitted in the last 12 months?</question>
        <help>&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Help:&lt;/strong&gt; Application volume helps test whether the issue is too few asks, limited targeting, low conversion, or over-application to low-fit calls.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Example:&lt;/strong&gt; Use the safest accurate answer. If exact details create risk, use an approximate answer or choose Not applicable / Unsafe to answer.&lt;/p&gt;</help>
        <script />
        <language>en</language>
      </row>
      <row>
        <id>132</id>
        <qid>251</qid>
        <question>How many funding applications or asks were successful in the last 12 months?</question>
        <help>&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Help:&lt;/strong&gt; Success count helps calculate conversion pattern. Include grants, renewals, small awards, fiscal-hosted funds, and confirmed paid partnerships if relevant.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Example:&lt;/strong&gt; Use the safest accurate answer. If exact details create risk, use an approximate answer or choose Not applicable / Unsafe to answer.&lt;/p&gt;</help>
        <script />
        <language>en</language>
      </row>
      <row>
        <id>155</id>
        <qid>257</qid>
        <question>How public can the organisation safely be in funder-facing materials?</question>
        <help>&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Help:&lt;/strong&gt; Public visibility can help credibility, but it can also create risk. Choose the safest honest level for funder-facing materials.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Example:&lt;/strong&gt; Use the safest accurate answer. If exact details create risk, use an approximate answer or choose Not applicable / Unsafe to answer.&lt;/p&gt;</help>
        <script />
        <language>en</language>
      </row>
      <row>
        <id>169</id>
        <qid>261</qid>
        <question>At which stage do funding opportunities most often lose momentum?</question>
        <help>&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Help:&lt;/strong&gt; Choose the stage where opportunities most often slow down, go silent, receive a no, become unsafe, or stop moving forward.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Example:&lt;/strong&gt; Choose one stage. Later questions capture common rejection signals, follow-up patterns and route readiness.&lt;/p&gt;</help>
        <script />
        <language>en</language>
      </row>
      <row>
        <id>178</id>
        <qid>262</qid>
        <question>Which types of funding opportunities do you usually pursue? Select all that apply.</question>
        <help>&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Help:&lt;/strong&gt; This shows whether the organisation is mostly spending energy on open calls, relationship routes, renewals, intermediaries or safer alternatives.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Example:&lt;/strong&gt; Select the routes you usually try, not only the most recent opportunity.&lt;/p&gt;</help>
        <script />
        <language>en</language>
      </row>
      <row>
        <id>179</id>
        <qid>263</qid>
        <question>Which funder types usually reject, decline, or do not respond to you? Select all that apply.</question>
        <help>&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Help:&lt;/strong&gt; Different funder types reject for different reasons. This helps the report avoid treating all “no” responses as the same barrier.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Example:&lt;/strong&gt; Select the types of funders where applications, concept notes, conversations or renewals most often do not convert.&lt;/p&gt;</help>
        <script />
        <language>en</language>
      </row>
      <row>
        <id>180</id>
        <qid>264</qid>
        <question>Which funding routes do you usually use when approaching funders? Select all that apply.</question>
        <help>&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Help:&lt;/strong&gt; The route is the path into the funder, not only the funder name. Select every route you commonly use. If one route dominates, select only that route.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Example:&lt;/strong&gt; You might use cold public calls, warm introductions, a fiscal host, a regrantor, renewals, a coalition route or rapid-response funding. The detailed route readiness matrix appears later.&lt;/p&gt;</help>
        <script />
        <language>en</language>
      </row>
      <row>
        <id>184</id>
        <qid>268</qid>
        <question>What result is most common across lost or stalled funding opportunities?</question>
        <help>&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Help:&lt;/strong&gt; This helps separate clear rejection, silence, partial interest, pending responses and delayed opportunities.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Example:&lt;/strong&gt; Choose the result that happens most often across the funding opportunities that do not convert.&lt;/p&gt;</help>
        <script />
        <language>en</language>
      </row>
      <row>
        <id>185</id>
        <qid>269</qid>
        <question>What feedback, signals, or rejection reasons are most common across lost applications? Select all that apply.</question>
        <help>&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Help:&lt;/strong&gt; This helps separate fit, proof, trust, route, timing and context barriers instead of treating every “no” as a writing problem.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Example:&lt;/strong&gt; Select formal feedback, informal signals, repeated silences, or patterns the team has observed across lost funding opportunities.&lt;/p&gt;</help>
        <script />
        <language>en</language>
      </row>
      <row>
        <id>186</id>
        <qid>270</qid>
        <question>After a funder says no, goes silent, or delays a decision, what follow-up usually happens?</question>
        <help>&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Help:&lt;/strong&gt; Follow-up affects relationships, learning and future conversion. This question checks whether rejection becomes intelligence or disappears from the system.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Example:&lt;/strong&gt; Think about thanks, feedback requests, relationship updates, document repairs, funder-map updates and next-step agreements.&lt;/p&gt;</help>
        <script />
        <language>en</language>
      </row>
      <row>
        <id>187</id>
        <qid>271</qid>
        <question>What usually changes after a lost, stalled, or declined funding attempt? Select all that apply.</question>
        <help>&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Help:&lt;/strong&gt; This checks whether funding attempts create learning, repair, relationship-building or only another submission cycle.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Example:&lt;/strong&gt; Select changes to your funder map, evidence pack, proposal, budget, documents, route strategy, follow-up rhythm, or team learning.&lt;/p&gt;</help>
        <script />
        <language>en</language>
      </row>
      <row>
        <id>211</id>
        <qid>295</qid>
        <question>Does your organisation target funders that currently fund your issue or field?</question>
        <help>&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Help:&lt;/strong&gt; This matters because funders first filter for fit. Answer from current funder evidence, recent calls, grant history, and whether the ask genuinely matches your work.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Example:&lt;/strong&gt; Look at recent calls, funder strategy pages, past grant lists, and grants to organisations doing similar work.&lt;/p&gt;</help>
        <script />
        <language>en</language>
      </row>
      <row>
        <id>212</id>
        <qid>296</qid>
        <question>Does your organisation target funders that currently fund your geography (country, region, area)?</question>
        <help>&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Help:&lt;/strong&gt; This matters because funders first filter for fit. Answer from current funder evidence, recent calls, grant history, and whether the ask genuinely matches your work.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Example:&lt;/strong&gt; Look at recent calls, funder strategy pages, past grant lists, and grants to organisations doing similar work.&lt;/p&gt;</help>
        <script />
        <language>en</language>
      </row>
      <row>
        <id>213</id>
        <qid>297</qid>
        <question>Does your organisation target funders that currently support your stage of development (e.g., startup under 2 years, mature 5+ years)?</question>
        <help>&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Help:&lt;/strong&gt; This matters because funders first filter for fit. Answer from current funder evidence, recent calls, grant history, and whether the ask genuinely matches your work.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Example:&lt;/strong&gt; Look at recent calls, funder strategy pages, past grant lists, and grants to organisations doing similar work.&lt;/p&gt;</help>
        <script />
        <language>en</language>
      </row>
      <row>
        <id>214</id>
        <qid>298</qid>
        <question>Does your organisation target funders that accept your registration or legal status?</question>
        <help>&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Help:&lt;/strong&gt; This matters because funders first filter for fit. Answer from current funder evidence, recent calls, grant history, and whether the ask genuinely matches your work.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Example:&lt;/strong&gt; Look at recent calls, funder strategy pages, past grant lists, and grants to organisations doing similar work.&lt;/p&gt;</help>
        <script />
        <language>en</language>
      </row>
      <row>
        <id>215</id>
        <qid>299</qid>
        <question>Does the type of work you do fit what your target funders currently fund?</question>
        <help>&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Help:&lt;/strong&gt; This matters because funders first filter for fit. Answer from current funder evidence, recent calls, grant history, and whether the ask genuinely matches your work.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Example:&lt;/strong&gt; Look at recent calls, funder strategy pages, past grant lists, and grants to organisations doing similar work.&lt;/p&gt;</help>
        <script />
        <language>en</language>
      </row>
      <row>
        <id>216</id>
        <qid>300</qid>
        <question>Do your target funders currently offer the grant type you need?</question>
        <help>&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Help:&lt;/strong&gt; This matters because funders first filter for fit. Answer from current funder evidence, recent calls, grant history, and whether the ask genuinely matches your work.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Example:&lt;/strong&gt; Look at recent calls, funder strategy pages, past grant lists, and grants to organisations doing similar work.&lt;/p&gt;</help>
        <script />
        <language>en</language>
      </row>
      <row>
        <id>217</id>
        <qid>301</qid>
        <question>Does your typical request amount fit the funder’s usual grant size?</question>
        <help>&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Help:&lt;/strong&gt; This matters because funders first filter for fit. Answer from current funder evidence, recent calls, grant history, and whether the ask genuinely matches your work.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Example:&lt;/strong&gt; Look at recent calls, funder strategy pages, past grant lists, and grants to organisations doing similar work.&lt;/p&gt;</help>
        <script />
        <language>en</language>
      </row>
      <row>
        <id>218</id>
        <qid>302</qid>
        <question>Does the request amount fit your organisation’s budget, track record, and systems?</question>
        <help>&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Help:&lt;/strong&gt; This matters because funders first filter for fit. Answer from current funder evidence, recent calls, grant history, and whether the ask genuinely matches your work.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Example:&lt;/strong&gt; Look at recent calls, funder strategy pages, past grant lists, and grants to organisations doing similar work.&lt;/p&gt;</help>
        <script />
        <language>en</language>
      </row>
      <row>
        <id>219</id>
        <qid>303</qid>
        <question>Does your organisation apply to funders and grants that would not distort your mission, politics, community accountability, or safety?</question>
        <help>&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Help:&lt;/strong&gt; This matters because funders first filter for fit. Answer from current funder evidence, recent calls, grant history, and whether the ask genuinely matches your work.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Example:&lt;/strong&gt; Look at recent calls, funder strategy pages, past grant lists, and grants to organisations doing similar work.&lt;/p&gt;</help>
        <script />
        <language>en</language>
      </row>
      <row>
        <id>220</id>
        <qid>304</qid>
        <question>Can your organisation clearly articulate what makes your approach, team, community relationship, or model different from others doing similar work?</question>
        <help>&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Help:&lt;/strong&gt; This matters because funders first filter for fit. Answer from current funder evidence, recent calls, grant history, and whether the ask genuinely matches your work.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Example:&lt;/strong&gt; Look at recent calls, funder strategy pages, past grant lists, and grants to organisations doing similar work.&lt;/p&gt;</help>
        <script />
        <language>en</language>
      </row>
      <row>
        <id>221</id>
        <qid>305</qid>
        <question>Is your governance or oversight body active and documented?</question>
        <help>&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Help:&lt;/strong&gt; This matters because organisational signals help funders verify that the organisation is real, governed, and able to handle funds responsibly.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Example:&lt;/strong&gt; Think about governance records, finance rules, approval roles, verification documents, public signals, and what a funder could check.&lt;/p&gt;</help>
        <script />
        <language>en</language>
      </row>
      <row>
        <id>222</id>
        <qid>306</qid>
        <question>Does your board or oversight body include the expertise funders need to trust the organisation?</question>
        <help>&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Help:&lt;/strong&gt; This matters because organisational signals help funders verify that the organisation is real, governed, and able to handle funds responsibly.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Example:&lt;/strong&gt; Think about governance records, finance rules, approval roles, verification documents, public signals, and what a funder could check.&lt;/p&gt;</help>
        <script />
        <language>en</language>
      </row>
      <row>
        <id>224</id>
        <qid>308</qid>
        <question>Are finance rules for approving and recording spending active?</question>
        <help>&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Help:&lt;/strong&gt; This matters because organisational signals help funders verify that the organisation is real, governed, and able to handle funds responsibly.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Example:&lt;/strong&gt; Think about governance records, finance rules, approval roles, verification documents, public signals, and what a funder could check.&lt;/p&gt;</help>
        <script />
        <language>en</language>
      </row>
      <row>
        <id>225</id>
        <qid>309</qid>
        <question>Do at least two people approve or check payments, especially larger amounts?</question>
        <help>&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Help:&lt;/strong&gt; This matters because organisational signals help funders verify that the organisation is real, governed, and able to handle funds responsibly.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Example:&lt;/strong&gt; Think about governance records, finance rules, approval roles, verification documents, public signals, and what a funder could check.&lt;/p&gt;</help>
        <script />
        <language>en</language>
      </row>
      <row>
        <id>226</id>
        <qid>310</qid>
        <question>Are financial records current enough to support a funding application?</question>
        <help>&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Help:&lt;/strong&gt; This matters because organisational signals help funders verify that the organisation is real, governed, and able to handle funds responsibly.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Example:&lt;/strong&gt; Think about governance records, finance rules, approval roles, verification documents, public signals, and what a funder could check.&lt;/p&gt;</help>
        <script />
        <language>en</language>
      </row>
      <row>
        <id>227</id>
        <qid>311</qid>
        <question>Are conflict-of-interest rules in place and used?</question>
        <help>&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Help:&lt;/strong&gt; This matters because organisational signals help funders verify that the organisation is real, governed, and able to handle funds responsibly.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Example:&lt;/strong&gt; Think about governance records, finance rules, approval roles, verification documents, public signals, and what a funder could check.&lt;/p&gt;</help>
        <script />
        <language>en</language>
      </row>
      <row>
        <id>229</id>
        <qid>313</qid>
        <question>Can your organisation be verified through reliable public information?</question>
        <help>&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Help:&lt;/strong&gt; If a funder searches for you online, can they find proof that you are active and legitimate?&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Example:&lt;/strong&gt; This includes a website, social media pages that show your work, or mentions in public reports/news that demonstrate you are doing what you claim. If visibility is unsafe, choose the safest accurate option.&lt;/p&gt;</help>
        <script />
        <language>en</language>
      </row>
      <row>
        <id>230</id>
        <qid>314</qid>
        <question>Can your work be explained and understood by someone outside the organisation in two simple sentences?</question>
        <help>&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Help:&lt;/strong&gt; This matters because reviewers need to understand, believe, and repeat your value case quickly. Think about clarity, proof, specificity, and dignity.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Example:&lt;/strong&gt; Think about your profile, concept notes, proposals, budgets, stories, evidence, and whether someone outside the work can understand the value.&lt;/p&gt;</help>
        <script />
        <language>en</language>
      </row>
      <row>
        <id>231</id>
        <qid>315</qid>
        <question>Is your change logic clearly mapped from activities to the changes they create?</question>
        <help>&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Help:&lt;/strong&gt; This matters because reviewers need to understand, believe, and repeat your value case quickly. Think about clarity, proof, specificity, and dignity.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Example:&lt;/strong&gt; Think about your profile, concept notes, proposals, budgets, stories, evidence, and whether someone outside the work can understand the value.&lt;/p&gt;</help>
        <script />
        <language>en</language>
      </row>
      <row>
        <id>232</id>
        <qid>316</qid>
        <question>Is the problem you address specific and bounded enough for funders to understand?</question>
        <help>&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Help:&lt;/strong&gt; This matters because reviewers need to understand, believe, and repeat your value case quickly. Think about clarity, proof, specificity, and dignity.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Example:&lt;/strong&gt; Think about your profile, concept notes, proposals, budgets, stories, evidence, and whether someone outside the work can understand the value.&lt;/p&gt;</help>
        <script />
        <language>en</language>
      </row>
      <row>
        <id>233</id>
        <qid>317</qid>
        <question>Can you show the real impact of your work?</question>
        <help>&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Help:&lt;/strong&gt; This matters because reviewers need to understand, believe, and repeat your value case quickly. Think about clarity, proof, specificity, and dignity.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Example:&lt;/strong&gt; Think about your profile, concept notes, proposals, budgets, stories, evidence, and whether someone outside the work can understand the value.&lt;/p&gt;</help>
        <script />
        <language>en</language>
      </row>
      <row>
        <id>234</id>
        <qid>318</qid>
        <question>Are your narrative assets ready for funding conversations?</question>
        <help>&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Help:&lt;/strong&gt; This matters because reviewers need to understand, believe, and repeat your value case quickly. Think about clarity, proof, specificity, and dignity.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Example:&lt;/strong&gt; Think about your profile, concept notes, proposals, budgets, stories, evidence, and whether someone outside the work can understand the value.&lt;/p&gt;</help>
        <script />
        <language>en</language>
      </row>
      <row>
        <id>235</id>
        <qid>319</qid>
        <question>Is your evidence of work and results ready for funder conversations?</question>
        <help>&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Help:&lt;/strong&gt; Funders need proof they can understand, trust, and repeat in their own decision spaces. This question checks whether your evidence supports your claims without exposing people or communities.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Example:&lt;/strong&gt; This may include safe case examples, partner feedback, outcome records, attendance data, learning reports, testimonials, or community validation.&lt;/p&gt;</help>
        <script />
        <language>en</language>
      </row>
      <row>
        <id>236</id>
        <qid>320</qid>
        <question>Are community stories consent-based and dignity-preserving?</question>
        <help>&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Help:&lt;/strong&gt; This matters because reviewers need to understand, believe, and repeat your value case quickly. Think about clarity, proof, specificity, and dignity.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Example:&lt;/strong&gt; Think about your profile, concept notes, proposals, budgets, stories, evidence, and whether someone outside the work can understand the value.&lt;/p&gt;</help>
        <script />
        <language>en</language>
      </row>
      <row>
        <id>237</id>
        <qid>321</qid>
        <question>Do your proposals show why you are well placed to do the work beyond identity alone?</question>
        <help>&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Help:&lt;/strong&gt; This matters because reviewers need to understand, believe, and repeat your value case quickly. Think about clarity, proof, specificity, and dignity.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Example:&lt;/strong&gt; Think about your profile, concept notes, proposals, budgets, stories, evidence, and whether someone outside the work can understand the value.&lt;/p&gt;</help>
        <script />
        <language>en</language>
      </row>
      <row>
        <id>238</id>
        <qid>322</qid>
        <question>Do your budget, workplan, and narrative tell the same coherent story?</question>
        <help>&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Help:&lt;/strong&gt; This matters because reviewers need to understand, believe, and repeat your value case quickly. Think about clarity, proof, specificity, and dignity.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Example:&lt;/strong&gt; Think about your profile, concept notes, proposals, budgets, stories, evidence, and whether someone outside the work can understand the value.&lt;/p&gt;</help>
        <script />
        <language>en</language>
      </row>
      <row>
        <id>239</id>
        <qid>323</qid>
        <question>Does your funding language feel grounded, human, specific, and connected to real work?</question>
        <help>&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Help:&lt;/strong&gt; This matters because reviewers need to understand, believe, and repeat your value case quickly. Think about clarity, proof, specificity, and dignity.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Example:&lt;/strong&gt; Think about your profile, concept notes, proposals, budgets, stories, evidence, and whether someone outside the work can understand the value.&lt;/p&gt;</help>
        <script />
        <language>en</language>
      </row>
      <row>
        <id>244</id>
        <qid>328</qid>
        <question>Would your records and reports match reality if respectfully spot-checked?</question>
        <help>&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Help:&lt;/strong&gt; This matters because trust is a funding threshold. Answer based on documented practice, community accountability, safeguarding, reputation, and what would stand up to a check.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Example:&lt;/strong&gt; Think about records, community accountability, safeguarding, references, past funders, and what would stand up to a respectful due-diligence check.&lt;/p&gt;</help>
        <script />
        <language>en</language>
      </row>
      <row>
        <id>245</id>
        <qid>329</qid>
        <question>Are safeguarding or harm-prevention policies and practices active?</question>
        <help>&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Help:&lt;/strong&gt; Funders may look for evidence that harm-prevention is not only written down but actually used.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Example:&lt;/strong&gt; This includes safeguarding practice, referral routes, induction, reporting protection, and people knowing what to do if harm or risk appears.&lt;/p&gt;</help>
        <script />
        <language>en</language>
      </row>
      <row>
        <id>246</id>
        <qid>330</qid>
        <question>Does your organisation have safe complaints and whistleblowing routes that people trust?</question>
        <help>&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Help:&lt;/strong&gt; Safe complaints and whistleblowing routes protect communities, staff, partners and the organisation.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Example:&lt;/strong&gt; Think about whether people know the route, trust it, and can use it without fear of exposure or retaliation.&lt;/p&gt;</help>
        <script />
        <language>en</language>
      </row>
      <row>
        <id>248</id>
        <qid>332</qid>
        <question>Can credible people or organisations in your movement or area vouch for your work?</question>
        <help>&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Help:&lt;/strong&gt; This matters because trust is a funding threshold. Answer based on documented practice, community accountability, safeguarding, reputation, and what would stand up to a check.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Example:&lt;/strong&gt; Think about records, community accountability, safeguarding, references, past funders, and what would stand up to a respectful due-diligence check.&lt;/p&gt;</help>
        <script />
        <language>en</language>
      </row>
      <row>
        <id>249</id>
        <qid>333</qid>
        <question>What do previous grants or funded partnerships say about your reliability and funding reputation?</question>
        <help>&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Help:&lt;/strong&gt; Past grant behaviour is often read as a trust signal. This question checks whether previous delivery, reporting, communication and close-out strengthen or weaken funder confidence.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Example:&lt;/strong&gt; Think about whether previous funders would say funds were used responsibly, reports were timely, changes were communicated, and the relationship ended cleanly.&lt;/p&gt;</help>
        <script />
        <language>en</language>
      </row>
      <row>
        <id>250</id>
        <qid>334</qid>
        <question>Does each major activity have a named person responsible?</question>
        <help>&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Help:&lt;/strong&gt; This matters because funding can fail after approval if delivery, finance, reporting, or team capacity cannot carry the grant safely.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Example:&lt;/strong&gt; Think about workplans, team capacity, grant tracking, finance records, reporting habits, and continuity if key people are unavailable.&lt;/p&gt;</help>
        <script />
        <language>en</language>
      </row>
      <row>
        <id>251</id>
        <qid>335</qid>
        <question>Do the people delivering the work have the skills and support required?</question>
        <help>&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Help:&lt;/strong&gt; This matters because funding can fail after approval if delivery, finance, reporting, or team capacity cannot carry the grant safely.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Example:&lt;/strong&gt; Think about workplans, team capacity, grant tracking, finance records, reporting habits, and continuity if key people are unavailable.&lt;/p&gt;</help>
        <script />
        <language>en</language>
      </row>
      <row>
        <id>252</id>
        <qid>336</qid>
        <question>Is team stretch or fatigue manageable enough for safe delivery?</question>
        <help>&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Help:&lt;/strong&gt; This matters because funding can fail after approval if delivery, finance, reporting, or team capacity cannot carry the grant safely.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Example:&lt;/strong&gt; Think about workplans, team capacity, grant tracking, finance records, reporting habits, and continuity if key people are unavailable.&lt;/p&gt;</help>
        <script />
        <language>en</language>
      </row>
      <row>
        <id>254</id>
        <qid>338</qid>
        <question>Are financial and narrative reports produced on time and strong enough to support future funding?</question>
        <help>&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Help:&lt;/strong&gt; Reporting is not only compliance. Strong reports become proof that the organisation can deliver, learn and use funds responsibly.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Example:&lt;/strong&gt; Think about reports sent to funders, board reports, donor updates, financial reports and close-out reports.&lt;/p&gt;</help>
        <script />
        <language>en</language>
      </row>
      <row>
        <id>255</id>
        <qid>339</qid>
        <question>Is every expense recorded and receipted with date, amount, purpose, and budget line?</question>
        <help>&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Help:&lt;/strong&gt; This matters because funding can fail after approval if delivery, finance, reporting, or team capacity cannot carry the grant safely.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Example:&lt;/strong&gt; Think about workplans, team capacity, grant tracking, finance records, reporting habits, and continuity if key people are unavailable.&lt;/p&gt;</help>
        <script />
        <language>en</language>
      </row>
      <row>
        <id>256</id>
        <qid>340</qid>
        <question>Does your organisation have accounting software or structured spreadsheets for financial tracking?</question>
        <help>&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Help:&lt;/strong&gt; This matters because funding can fail after approval if delivery, finance, reporting, or team capacity cannot carry the grant safely.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Example:&lt;/strong&gt; Think about workplans, team capacity, grant tracking, finance records, reporting habits, and continuity if key people are unavailable.&lt;/p&gt;</help>
        <script />
        <language>en</language>
      </row>
      <row>
        <id>257</id>
        <qid>341</qid>
        <question>Does your organisation have live grant management systems to track grant budgets, restrictions, and reporting deadlines without losing them?</question>
        <help>&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Help:&lt;/strong&gt; This matters because funding can fail after approval if delivery, finance, reporting, or team capacity cannot carry the grant safely.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Example:&lt;/strong&gt; Think about workplans, team capacity, grant tracking, finance records, reporting habits, and continuity if key people are unavailable.&lt;/p&gt;</help>
        <script />
        <language>en</language>
      </row>
      <row>
        <id>258</id>
        <qid>342</qid>
        <question>Are restricted or project funds separated from other funds?</question>
        <help>&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Help:&lt;/strong&gt; Funders check whether restricted or project money can be traced separately from other funds.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Example:&lt;/strong&gt; This may be through separate accounts, cost centres, project codes, spreadsheets, accounting software, reconciliations or clear manual records.&lt;/p&gt;</help>
        <script />
        <language>en</language>
      </row>
      <row>
        <id>260</id>
        <qid>344</qid>
        <question>Would the grant size you seek avoid unmanageable pressure or hidden labour?</question>
        <help>&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Help:&lt;/strong&gt; This matters because funding can fail after approval if delivery, finance, reporting, or team capacity cannot carry the grant safely.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Example:&lt;/strong&gt; Think about workplans, team capacity, grant tracking, finance records, reporting habits, and continuity if key people are unavailable.&lt;/p&gt;</help>
        <script />
        <language>en</language>
      </row>
      <row>
        <id>261</id>
        <qid>345</qid>
        <question>Does your organisation belong to relevant coalitions, networks, or movement spaces?</question>
        <help>&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Help:&lt;/strong&gt; This matters because access and relationships often determine whether strong work reaches the right room, reference, conversation, or referral.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Example:&lt;/strong&gt; Think about coalitions, peer relationships, shared work, referrals, introductions, and who would vouch for the organisation.&lt;/p&gt;</help>
        <script />
        <language>en</language>
      </row>
      <row>
        <id>266</id>
        <qid>350</qid>
        <question>Does your organisation have warm introductions or relationships with potential funders?</question>
        <help>&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Help:&lt;/strong&gt; This matters because access and relationships often determine whether strong work reaches the right room, reference, conversation, or referral.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Example:&lt;/strong&gt; Think about coalitions, peer relationships, shared work, referrals, introductions, and who would vouch for the organisation.&lt;/p&gt;</help>
        <script />
        <language>en</language>
      </row>
      <row>
        <id>267</id>
        <qid>351</qid>
        <question>Does your organisation proactively manage relationships with funders through updates and engagement?</question>
        <help>&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Help:&lt;/strong&gt; This matters because access and relationships often determine whether strong work reaches the right room, reference, conversation, or referral.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Example:&lt;/strong&gt; Think about coalitions, peer relationships, shared work, referrals, introductions, and who would vouch for the organisation.&lt;/p&gt;</help>
        <script />
        <language>en</language>
      </row>
      <row>
        <id>269</id>
        <qid>353</qid>
        <question>Do partners and peers include you in opportunities and referrals?</question>
        <help>&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Help:&lt;/strong&gt; This matters because access and relationships often determine whether strong work reaches the right room, reference, conversation, or referral.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Example:&lt;/strong&gt; Think about coalitions, peer relationships, shared work, referrals, introductions, and who would vouch for the organisation.&lt;/p&gt;</help>
        <script />
        <language>en</language>
      </row>
      <row>
        <id>273</id>
        <qid>357</qid>
        <question>In the last 12 months, how much have context changes affected your funding options negatively?</question>
        <help>&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Help:&lt;/strong&gt; This matters because context can limit funder appetite, delay transfers, increase safety risk, or require a different route even when the work is strong.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Example:&lt;/strong&gt; Think about civic space, safety, banking, currency, climate, politics, compliance, and alternative routes if direct funding is difficult.&lt;/p&gt;</help>
        <script />
        <language>en</language>
      </row>
      <row>
        <id>274</id>
        <qid>358</qid>
        <question>In the last 12 months, how often have funders cited context, risk, or compliance as blockers?</question>
        <help>&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Help:&lt;/strong&gt; This matters because context can limit funder appetite, delay transfers, increase safety risk, or require a different route even when the work is strong.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Example:&lt;/strong&gt; Think about civic space, safety, banking, currency, climate, politics, compliance, and alternative routes if direct funding is difficult.&lt;/p&gt;</help>
        <script />
        <language>en</language>
      </row>
      <row>
        <id>276</id>
        <qid>360</qid>
        <question>Is your country or region facing banking, currency, or transfer challenges?</question>
        <help>&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Help:&lt;/strong&gt; This matters because context can limit funder appetite, delay transfers, increase safety risk, or require a different route even when the work is strong.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Example:&lt;/strong&gt; Think about civic space, safety, banking, currency, climate, politics, compliance, and alternative routes if direct funding is difficult.&lt;/p&gt;</help>
        <script />
        <language>en</language>
      </row>
      <row>
        <id>277</id>
        <qid>361</qid>
        <question>If direct funding is blocked, does your organisation have alternative funding routes?</question>
        <help>&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Help:&lt;/strong&gt; This matters because context can limit funder appetite, delay transfers, increase safety risk, or require a different route even when the work is strong.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Example:&lt;/strong&gt; Think about civic space, safety, banking, currency, climate, politics, compliance, and alternative routes if direct funding is difficult.&lt;/p&gt;</help>
        <script />
        <language>en</language>
      </row>
      <row>
        <id>278</id>
        <qid>362</qid>
        <question>Is your work politically sensitive or structurally excluded in ways that limit funder appetite?</question>
        <help>&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Help:&lt;/strong&gt; This matters because context can limit funder appetite, delay transfers, increase safety risk, or require a different route even when the work is strong.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Example:&lt;/strong&gt; Think about civic space, safety, banking, currency, climate, politics, compliance, and alternative routes if direct funding is difficult.&lt;/p&gt;</help>
        <script />
        <language>en</language>
      </row>
      <row>
        <id>279</id>
        <qid>363</qid>
        <question>Do the funders you approach understand the operating realities, risks, and constraints of your context?</question>
        <help>&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Help:&lt;/strong&gt; This matters because context can limit funder appetite, delay transfers, increase safety risk, or require a different route even when the work is strong.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Example:&lt;/strong&gt; Think about civic space, safety, banking, currency, climate, politics, compliance, and alternative routes if direct funding is difficult.&lt;/p&gt;</help>
        <script />
        <language>en</language>
      </row>
      <row>
        <id>280</id>
        <qid>364</qid>
        <question>Does your organisation have a healthy number and set of identified potential funders?</question>
        <help>&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Help:&lt;/strong&gt; This matters because funder intelligence prevents wasted applications and helps the organisation act at the right time, through the right route, with the right evidence.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Example:&lt;/strong&gt; Think about your funder list, contacts, deadlines, routes, newsletters, briefings, and rapid-response opportunities.&lt;/p&gt;</help>
        <script />
        <language>en</language>
      </row>
      <row>
        <id>282</id>
        <qid>366</qid>
        <question>Does your organisation know when target funder types open calls or refresh strategies?</question>
        <help>&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Help:&lt;/strong&gt; This matters because funder intelligence prevents wasted applications and helps the organisation act at the right time, through the right route, with the right evidence.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Example:&lt;/strong&gt; Think about your funder list, contacts, deadlines, routes, newsletters, briefings, and rapid-response opportunities.&lt;/p&gt;</help>
        <script />
        <language>en</language>
      </row>
      <row>
        <id>283</id>
        <qid>367</qid>
        <question>Does your organisation track funder deadlines and cycles in a live system?</question>
        <help>&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Help:&lt;/strong&gt; This matters because funder intelligence prevents wasted applications and helps the organisation act at the right time, through the right route, with the right evidence.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Example:&lt;/strong&gt; Think about your funder list, contacts, deadlines, routes, newsletters, briefings, and rapid-response opportunities.&lt;/p&gt;</help>
        <script />
        <language>en</language>
      </row>
      <row>
        <id>284</id>
        <qid>368</qid>
        <question>Can your organisation respond to fast-turnaround opportunities within 2 weeks?</question>
        <help>&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Help:&lt;/strong&gt; This matters because funder intelligence prevents wasted applications and helps the organisation act at the right time, through the right route, with the right evidence.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Example:&lt;/strong&gt; Think about your funder list, contacts, deadlines, routes, newsletters, briefings, and rapid-response opportunities.&lt;/p&gt;</help>
        <script />
        <language>en</language>
      </row>
      <row>
        <id>285</id>
        <qid>369</qid>
        <question>Does your organisation know when funders have unspent budget, urgent gaps, or rapid-response opportunities?</question>
        <help>&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Help:&lt;/strong&gt; This matters because funder intelligence prevents wasted applications and helps the organisation act at the right time, through the right route, with the right evidence.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Example:&lt;/strong&gt; Think about your funder list, contacts, deadlines, routes, newsletters, briefings, and rapid-response opportunities.&lt;/p&gt;</help>
        <script />
        <language>en</language>
      </row>
      <row>
        <id>286</id>
        <qid>370</qid>
        <question>Does your organisation know the access route for each priority funder, such as open call, invitation, fiscal host, intermediary, consortium, emergency route, or warm introduction?</question>
        <help>&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Help:&lt;/strong&gt; This matters because funder intelligence prevents wasted applications and helps the organisation act at the right time, through the right route, with the right evidence.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Example:&lt;/strong&gt; Think about your funder list, contacts, deadlines, routes, newsletters, briefings, and rapid-response opportunities.&lt;/p&gt;</help>
        <script />
        <language>en</language>
      </row>
      <row>
        <id>293</id>
        <qid>377</qid>
        <question>Is your organisation protected from overdependence on one funder, one grant, or one short funding cycle?</question>
        <help>&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Help:&lt;/strong&gt; This matters because funders look for continuity, ownership, and realistic true-cost planning rather than work that collapses when one grant or person changes.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Example:&lt;/strong&gt; Look at recent calls, funder strategy pages, past grant lists, and grants to organisations doing similar work.&lt;/p&gt;</help>
        <script />
        <language>en</language>
      </row>
      <row>
        <id>294</id>
        <qid>378</qid>
        <question>Does your organisation have a realistic plan for core costs, reserves, or continuity between grants?</question>
        <help>&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Help:&lt;/strong&gt; This matters because funders look for continuity, ownership, and realistic true-cost planning rather than work that collapses when one grant or person changes.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Example:&lt;/strong&gt; Look at recent calls, funder strategy pages, past grant lists, and grants to organisations doing similar work.&lt;/p&gt;</help>
        <script />
        <language>en</language>
      </row>
      <row>
        <id>295</id>
        <qid>379</qid>
        <question>Is the work protected from depending on one person for relationships, knowledge, or decisions?</question>
        <help>&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Help:&lt;/strong&gt; This matters because funders look for continuity, ownership, and realistic true-cost planning rather than work that collapses when one grant or person changes.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Example:&lt;/strong&gt; Look at recent calls, funder strategy pages, past grant lists, and grants to organisations doing similar work.&lt;/p&gt;</help>
        <script />
        <language>en</language>
      </row>
      <row>
        <id>297</id>
        <qid>381</qid>
        <question>Can your organisation explain what should be sustained, what should grow, and what should end if funding changes?</question>
        <help>&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Help:&lt;/strong&gt; This matters because funders look for continuity, ownership, and realistic true-cost planning rather than work that collapses when one grant or person changes.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Example:&lt;/strong&gt; Look at recent calls, funder strategy pages, past grant lists, and grants to organisations doing similar work.&lt;/p&gt;</help>
        <script />
        <language>en</language>
      </row>
      <row>
        <id>298</id>
        <qid>382</qid>
        <question>Do previous funders or partners create realistic renewal, bridge-funding, or referral routes?</question>
        <help>&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Help:&lt;/strong&gt; A past relationship can become a future route if it has been maintained and the funder still understands the value of the work.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Example:&lt;/strong&gt; Think about funders, fiscal hosts, partners or peers who could renew support, bridge a gap, introduce you, or vouch for you.&lt;/p&gt;</help>
        <script />
        <language>en</language>
      </row>
      <row>
        <id>299</id>
        <qid>383</qid>
        <question>Does your organisation understand the true cost of delivery, including hidden labour, care, admin, safeguarding, reporting, and learning?</question>
        <help>&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Help:&lt;/strong&gt; This matters because funders look for continuity, ownership, and realistic true-cost planning rather than work that collapses when one grant or person changes.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Example:&lt;/strong&gt; Look at recent calls, funder strategy pages, past grant lists, and grants to organisations doing similar work.&lt;/p&gt;</help>
        <script />
        <language>en</language>
      </row>
      <row>
        <id>301</id>
        <qid>385</qid>
        <question>Does your organisation have a written fundraising or resourcing strategy with priorities, timelines, owners, and review rhythm?</question>
        <help>&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Help:&lt;/strong&gt; This matters because fundraising converts better when it is a disciplined system with ethics, review, follow-up, and learning rather than rushed proposal production.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Example:&lt;/strong&gt; Look at recent calls, funder strategy pages, past grant lists, and grants to organisations doing similar work.&lt;/p&gt;</help>
        <script />
        <language>en</language>
      </row>
      <row>
        <id>302</id>
        <qid>386</qid>
        <question>Does your organisation maintain a live funder pipeline or CRM with prospects, routes, deadlines, contacts, and next actions?</question>
        <help>&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Help:&lt;/strong&gt; This matters because fundraising converts better when it is a disciplined system with ethics, review, follow-up, and learning rather than rushed proposal production.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Example:&lt;/strong&gt; Look at recent calls, funder strategy pages, past grant lists, and grants to organisations doing similar work.&lt;/p&gt;</help>
        <script />
        <language>en</language>
      </row>
      <row>
        <id>303</id>
        <qid>387</qid>
        <question>Before applying, do you check fit, route, evidence, documents, safety, and relationship position?</question>
        <help>&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Help:&lt;/strong&gt; A strong go/no-go check protects the team from spending energy on low-fit opportunities. This question checks whether proposal effort begins only after fit and route have been tested.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Example:&lt;/strong&gt; Before writing, you would confirm the funder mandate, grant size, deadline, relationship route, required documents, evidence needs, and safety risks.&lt;/p&gt;</help>
        <script />
        <language>en</language>
      </row>
      <row>
        <id>307</id>
        <qid>391</qid>
        <question>What is the current readiness status of each document or evidence item?</question>
        <help>&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Help:&lt;/strong&gt; This checks whether each document exists, is current, can be found, and can be shared safely. Protected evidence is not missing evidence.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Example:&lt;/strong&gt; For each item, choose the option that best reflects its current readiness for due diligence, redaction, private verification or funder review.&lt;/p&gt;</help>
        <script />
        <language>en</language>
      </row>
      <row>
        <id>308</id>
        <qid>5140</qid>
        <question>Registration, legal-status, or fiscal-host proof</question>
