      <row>
        <id>429</id>
        <qid>5257</qid>
        <question>Corporate or CSR route</question>
        <help />
        <script />
        <language>en</language>
      </row>
      <row>
        <id>430</id>
        <qid>5258</qid>
        <question>Direct institutional grant to the organisation</question>
        <help />
        <script />
        <language>en</language>
      </row>
      <row>
        <id>431</id>
        <qid>5259</qid>
        <question>Pause and repair before applying</question>
        <help />
        <script />
        <language>en</language>
      </row>
      <row>
        <id>432</id>
        <qid>5260</qid>
        <question>How strong are the proposal quality-control checks before anything is submitted?</question>
        <help>&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Help:&lt;/strong&gt; Proposal review is where many applications stop. This matrix checks whether avoidable submission problems are being caught before the funder sees them.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Example:&lt;/strong&gt; A strong proposal process checks fit, attachments, budget logic, safety and submission readiness before the final upload or email.&lt;/p&gt;</help>
        <script />
        <language>en</language>
      </row>
      <row>
        <id>433</id>
        <qid>5261</qid>
        <question>Funder-specific tailoring: the proposal clearly shows why this funder, why now, and why this route.</question>
        <help />
        <script />
        <language>en</language>
      </row>
      <row>
        <id>434</id>
        <qid>5262</qid>
        <question>Mandatory attachment check: required files, names, formats, signatures, and portal fields are checked before upload.</question>
        <help />
        <script />
        <language>en</language>
      </row>
      <row>
        <id>435</id>
        <qid>5263</qid>
        <question>Budget, workplan, and narrative alignment: the story, activities, timelines, and costs tell the same story.</question>
        <help />
        <script />
        <language>en</language>
      </row>
      <row>
        <id>436</id>
        <qid>5264</qid>
        <question>Internal review gate: someone other than the writer checks fit, risk, clarity, and completeness.</question>
        <help />
        <script />
        <language>en</language>
      </row>
      <row>
        <id>437</id>
        <qid>5265</qid>
        <question>Submission buffer: the team submits early enough to fix portal, file, approval, or internet problems.</question>
        <help />
        <script />
        <language>en</language>
      </row>
      <row>
        <id>438</id>
        <qid>5266</qid>
        <question>Safety and consent review: stories, photos, locations, and sensitive proof are checked before sharing.</question>
        <help />
        <script />
        <language>en</language>
      </row>
      <row>
        <id>439</id>
        <qid>5267</qid>
        <question>Which funding conversion pattern best describes what is happening right now?</question>
        <help>&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Help:&lt;/strong&gt; This is not asking you to diagnose yourself. It captures the pattern you are experiencing so the assessment can test what may be driving it.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Example:&lt;/strong&gt; Choose the option that best describes what usually happens across funding asks, applications, conversations, due diligence, awards or renewals.&lt;/p&gt;</help>
        <script />
        <language>en</language>
      </row>
      <row>
        <id>440</id>
        <qid>5268</qid>
        <question>Which other funding conversion patterns are also showing up? Select all that apply.</question>
        <help>&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Help:&lt;/strong&gt; Most conversion problems have more than one pattern. Select only the additional patterns that show up often enough to shape your funding results.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Example:&lt;/strong&gt; You might select silence, early rejection, weak renewal, due-diligence delays or safety/context barriers if they repeatedly affect different funding opportunities.&lt;/p&gt;</help>
        <script />
        <language>en</language>
      </row>
      <row>
        <id>441</id>
        <qid>5269</qid>
        <question>No serious funder conversations have happened yet.</question>
        <help />
        <script />
        <language>en</language>
      </row>
      <row>
        <id>442</id>
        <qid>5270</qid>
        <question>Applications or asks usually receive no response, silence, or very delayed responses.</question>
        <help />
        <script />
        <language>en</language>
      </row>
      <row>
        <id>443</id>
        <qid>5271</qid>
        <question>Opportunities are lost early because eligibility, geography, registration, route, or fit is uncertain.</question>
        <help />
        <script />
        <language>en</language>
      </row>
      <row>
        <id>444</id>
        <qid>5272</qid>
        <question>Applications reach proposal review but rarely move into shortlist, clarification, or due diligence.</question>
        <help />
        <script />
        <language>en</language>
      </row>
      <row>
        <id>445</id>
        <qid>5273</qid>
        <question>Funder conversations happen, but there is no clear next step, relationship path, or decision.</question>
        <help />
        <script />
        <language>en</language>
      </row>
      <row>
        <id>446</id>
        <qid>5274</qid>
        <question>Documents, policies, finance records, safeguarding, compliance, or verification slow down progress.</question>
        <help />
        <script />
        <language>en</language>
      </row>
      <row>
        <id>447</id>
        <qid>5275</qid>
        <question>Awards are too small, too short, too restricted, or not aligned with true delivery cost.</question>
        <help />
        <script />
        <language>en</language>
      </row>
      <row>
        <id>448</id>
        <qid>5276</qid>
        <question>Past grants do not turn into renewal, bridge funding, referrals, or repeat support.</question>
        <help />
        <script />
        <language>en</language>
      </row>
      <row>
        <id>449</id>
        <qid>5277</qid>
        <question>Context, safety, visibility, political sensitivity, banking, or transfer issues affect funder appetite.</question>
        <help />
        <script />
        <language>en</language>
      </row>
      <row>
        <id>450</id>
        <qid>5278</qid>
        <question>The team has limited time, systems, or confidence to follow up and learn from each attempt.</question>
        <help />
        <script />
        <language>en</language>
      </row>
      <row>
        <id>451</id>
        <qid>5279</qid>
        <question>No secondary pattern is clear right now.</question>
        <help />
        <script />
        <language>en</language>
      </row>
      <row>
        <id>452</id>
        <qid>5280</qid>
        <question>Prefer not to say / Unsafe to answer.</question>
        <help />
        <script />
        <language>en</language>
      </row>
      <row>
        <id>453</id>
        <qid>5281</qid>
        <question>Is authority to sign grant agreements clearly assigned and documented?</question>
        <help>&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Help:&lt;/strong&gt; Funders need to know who can legally and safely bind the organisation to a grant agreement.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Example:&lt;/strong&gt; Think about board resolutions, delegation letters, constitutions, fiscal-host agreements or other records showing who may sign.&lt;/p&gt;</help>
        <script />
        <language>en</language>
      </row>
      <row>
        <id>454</id>
        <qid>5282</qid>
        <question>Is authority to approve large spending clearly assigned and controlled?</question>
        <help>&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Help:&lt;/strong&gt; Grant-makers look for safe spending controls, especially when budgets grow or restricted funds are involved.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Example:&lt;/strong&gt; Think about approval thresholds, two-person checks, procurement rules, bank signatories and payment records.&lt;/p&gt;</help>
        <script />
        <language>en</language>
      </row>
      <row>
        <id>455</id>
        <qid>5283</qid>
        <question>How well are your proof and bargaining assets being used to increase funding opportunity and funder confidence?</question>
        <help>&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Help:&lt;/strong&gt; Many organisations already have assets that could strengthen funding conversion, but they are not always packaged, timed, or used strategically.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Example:&lt;/strong&gt; For each asset, choose how well it is being used in proposals, funder conversations, referrals, negotiation, or renewal discussions.&lt;/p&gt;</help>
        <script />
        <language>en</language>
      </row>
      <row>
        <id>456</id>
        <qid>5284</qid>
        <question>How strong is your reporting evidence as credible proof for funders?</question>
        <help>&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Help:&lt;/strong&gt; Reports can become proof assets when they show delivery, learning, use of funds, risks managed and results achieved.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Example:&lt;/strong&gt; Examples include narrative reports, financial reports, funder updates, board reports or close-out summaries.&lt;/p&gt;</help>
        <script />
        <language>en</language>
      </row>
      <row>
        <id>465</id>
        <qid>5293</qid>
        <question>Advocacy, campaigning, or policy influence</question>
        <help />
        <script />
        <language>en</language>
      </row>
      <row>
        <id>466</id>
        <qid>5294</qid>
        <question>Care, healing, wellbeing, or community support</question>
        <help />
        <script />
        <language>en</language>
      </row>
      <row>
        <id>467</id>
        <qid>5295</qid>
        <question>Convening, workshops, training, or movement building</question>
        <help />
        <script />
        <language>en</language>
      </row>
      <row>
        <id>468</id>
        <qid>5296</qid>
        <question>Core costs, operations, or organisational survival</question>
        <help />
        <script />
        <language>en</language>
      </row>
      <row>
        <id>469</id>
        <qid>5297</qid>
        <question>Digital systems, data systems, or technology</question>
        <help />
        <script />
        <language>en</language>
      </row>
      <row>
        <id>470</id>
        <qid>5298</qid>
        <question>Emergency response, crisis response, or rapid support</question>
        <help />
        <script />
        <language>en</language>
      </row>
      <row>
        <id>471</id>
        <qid>5299</qid>
        <question>Infrastructure, equipment, workspace, transport, or connectivity</question>
        <help />
        <script />
        <language>en</language>
      </row>
      <row>
        <id>472</id>
        <qid>5300</qid>
        <question>Monitoring, evaluation, learning, or evidence building</question>
        <help />
        <script />
        <language>en</language>
      </row>
      <row>
        <id>473</id>
        <qid>5301</qid>
        <question>Organisational strengthening, systems, or governance</question>
        <help />
        <script />
        <language>en</language>
